 Magazine]]\n[[Category:Victorian novels]]\n[[Category:Novels set in colonial Africa]]\n[[Category:Novels about colonialism]]\n[[Category:Novels about imperialism]]\n[[Category:British novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:1902 British novels]]\n[[Category:Human trophy collecting]]\n[[Category:Congo Free State]]\n[[Category:Travel novels]]\n[[Category:Novels adapted into television programs]]\n", "name_user": "2601:441:487f:2580:e81f:4b78:5164:5d27", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Entere)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart_of_Darkness"}
{"title_page": "Antonio Gala", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:ANTONIO GALA.jpg|thumb|250px|Antonio Gala]]\n'''Antonio Gala Velasco''' (born 2 October 1930) is a Spanish poet, playwright, novelist and writer.\n\n==Life and career==\nGala was born in [[Brazatortas]], [[Ciudad Real]] ([[Castile-La Mancha]]), although he moved very soon to [[C\u00f3rdoba (Spain)|C\u00f3rdoba]] and is widely considered an [[Andalusia]]n.\n\nA graduate in law, philosophy, politics and economics, he has written in a wide variety of genres, including journalism, short stories, essays and [[Teleplay|television script]]s. He has been awarded several prizes, not only within the field of poetry but also for his contributions to theatre and opera.\n\nGala's work has been more appreciated by his readership than by the critics, who find it hard to classify it due to its particular blend of lyricism and epic.\n\nAmong his most successful plays are ''Los verdes campos del Ed\u00e9n'' (''The Green Fields of Eden'', National Theatre Prize \"Calder\u00f3n de la Barca\" 1963), ''Anillos para una dama'' (''Rings for a Lady'', 1973), ''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 corres, Ulises?'' (''Why do you run, Ulysses?'', 1975), ''Petra Regalada'' (1980), ''Samarkanda'' (1985), ''Carmen, Carmen'' (1988) and ''La truhana'' (''The rogue'', 1992).\n\nAmong his collections of poetry are ''Sonetos de La Zubia'' (La Zubia Sonets), ''Poemas de amor'' (''Love Poems''), ''Testamento Andaluz'' (''Andalusian Will'') and ''Enemigo \u00edntimo'' (''Intimate Enemy'', Adonais Prize 1959).\n\nHe started to write novels late in life, but he obtained an overwhelming success with ''El manuscrito carmes\u00ed'' (''The Crimson Manuscript'', Planeta Prize 1990), ''\u00c1guila Bic\u00e9fala'' (''Two-Headed Eagle'', 1994), ''La regla de tres'' (''The Rule of Three'', 1996) and ''La pasi\u00f3n turca'' (''Turkish Passion'', 1993), adapted for the cinema by Spanish director [[Vicente Aranda]] and'' M\u00e1s all\u00e1 del Jard\u00edn'' (''Beyond the Garden'', 1995), adapted by [[Pedro Olea]].\n\nGala's literature is marked by historic issues, which are used more to lighten the present than to deepen in the past.\n\nHe is the current president of the International Theatre Institute.\n\n== Political views ==\nDuring the [[Spanish transition to democracy]] (1976 to the early 1980s) Gala publicly defended leftist political view points while not linked to a specific political party. In 1978 he called for a [[statute of autonomy]] for [[Andalusia]].<ref>[http://elpais.com/diario/1978/04/04/cultura/260488803_850215.html Apertura del Congreso de Cultura Andaluza]. El Pa\u00eds. 4 April 1978.</ref>\n\nIn 1981 he was named president of the Spanish-Arab Friendship Association, and fulfilled this role for the first years of existence of this association. Around the same time he joined the Spain-USSR Friendship Society.<ref>[http://cordobesesilustres.wikispaces.com/Antonio+Gala Cordobeses Ilustres de los siglos XIX y XX \u2013 Antonio Gala]</ref>\n\nHe was the president of the civic platform that defended the \"no\" to Spain's permanence in [[NATO]], in the 1986 [[Spanish NATO membership referendum, 1986|referendum]].<ref>Fran\u00e7oise Dubosquet Lairys, \"[http://cvc.cervantes.es/literatura/aih/pdf/13/aih_13_4_037.pdf Intelectual y prensa: Antonio Gala y ''El Independiente'']\", [[Instituto Cervantes]], accessed 9-April-2013.</ref>\n\nHe is the president of the [[Antonio Gala Foundation]] in the city of C\u00f3rdoba, Spain.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Caf\u00e9 Gij\u00f3n|Caf\u00e9 Gij\u00f3n (Madrid)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://amediavoz.com/gala.htm Some poems by Gala]\n*[http://www.antoniogala.es Antonio Gala's Official Site]\n{{commons category|Antonio Gala}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gala, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:Spanish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Ciudad Real]]\n[[Category:Spanish male poets]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n[[Image:ANTONIO GALA.jpg|thumb|250px|Antonio Gala]]\n'''Antonio Gala Velasco''' (born 2 October 1930) is a Spanish poet, playwright, novelist and writer.\n\n==Life and career==\nGala was born in [[Brazatortas]], [[Ciudad Real]] ([[Castile-La Mancha]]), although he moved very soon to [[C\u00f3rdoba (Spain)|C\u00f3rdoba]] and is widely considered an [[Andalusia]]n.\n\nA graduate in law, philosophy, politics and economics, he has written in a wide variety of genres, including journalism, short stories, essays and [[Teleplay|television script]]s. He has been awarded several prizes, not only within the field of poetry but also for his contributions to theatre and opera.\n\nGala's work has been more appreciated by his readership than by the critics, who find it hard to classify it due to its particular blend of lyricism and epic.\n\nAmong his most successful plays are ''Los verdes campos del Ed\u00e9n'' (''The Green Fields of Eden'', National Theatre Prize \"Calder\u00f3n de la Barca\" 1963), ''Anillos para una dama'' (''Rings for a Lady'', 1973), ''\u00bfPor qu\u00e9 corres, Ulises?'' (''Why do you run, Ulysses?'', 1975), ''Petra Regalada'' (1980), ''Samarkanda'' (1985), ''Carmen, Carmen'' (1988) and ''La truhana'' (''The rogue'', 1992).\n\nAmong his collections of poetry are ''Sonetos de La Zubia'' (La Zubia Sonets), ''Poemas de amor'' (''Love Poems''), ''Testamento Andaluz'' (''Andalusian Will'') and ''Enemigo \u00edntimo'' (''Intimate Enemy'', Adonais Prize 1959).\n\nHe started to write novels late in life, but he obtained an overwhelming success with ''El manuscrito carmes\u00ed'' (''The Crimson Manuscript'', Planeta Prize 1990), ''\u00c1guila Bic\u00e9fala'' (''Two-Headed Eagle'', 1994), ''La regla de tres'' (''The Rule of Three'', 1996) and ''La pasi\u00f3n turca'' (''Turkish Passion'', 1993), adapted for the cinema by Spanish director [[Vicente Aranda]] and'' M\u00e1s all\u00e1 del Jard\u00edn'' (''Beyond the Garden'', 1995), adapted by [[Pedro Olea]].\n\nGala's literature is marked by historic issues, which are used more to lighten the present than to deepen in the past.\n\nHe is the current president of the International Theatre Institute.\n\n== Political views ==\nDuring the [[Spanish transition to democracy]] (1976 to the early 1980s) Gala publicly defended leftist political view points while not linked to a specific political party. In 1978 he called for a [[statute of autonomy]] for [[Andalusia]].<ref>[http://elpais.com/diario/1978/04/04/cultura/260488803_850215.html Apertura del Congreso de Cultura Andaluza]. El Pa\u00eds. 4 April 1978.</ref>\n\nIn 1981 he was named president of the Spanish-Arab Friendship Association, and fulfilled this role for the first years of existence of this association. Around the same time he joined the Spain-USSR Friendship Society.<ref>[http://cordobesesilustres.wikispaces.com/Antonio+Gala Cordobeses Ilustres de los siglos XIX y XX \u2013 Antonio Gala]</ref>\n\nHe was the president of the civic platform that defended the \"no\" to Spain's permanence in [[NATO]], in the 1986 [[Spanish NATO membership referendum, 1986|referendum]].<ref>Fran\u00e7oise Dubosquet Lairys, \"[http://cvc.cervantes.es/literatura/aih/pdf/13/aih_13_4_037.pdf Intelectual y prensa: Antonio Gala y ''El Independiente'']\", [[Instituto Cervantes]], accessed 9-April-2013.</ref>\n\nHe is the president of the [[Antonio Gala Foundation]] in the city of C\u00f3rdoba, Spain.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Caf\u00e9 Gij\u00f3n|Caf\u00e9 Gij\u00f3n (Madrid)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://amediavoz.com/gala.htm Some poems by Gala]\n*[http://www.antoniogala.es Antonio Gala's Official Site]\n{{commons category|Antonio Gala}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gala, Antonio}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:Spanish male novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish male writers]]\n[[Category:People from Ciudad Real]]\n[[Category:Spanish male poets]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Bisexual writers]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add category", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Gala"}
{"title_page": "BIPIB", "text_new": "The '''Belgian Interdisciplinary Platform for Industrial Biotechnology''' or '''BIPIB''' is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] organization which consists of three working groups which come together on [[biomass]] supply, bioprocesses and [[bioproduct]]s, [[bio-energy]]. It was founded by [[Els Van Weert]], [[Flanders|Flemish]] secretary for [[sustainable development]] and [[social economy]]. The BIPIB was given the mission to provide advise for a long-term strategy for developing [[industrial biotechnology]] in Belgium.\n\nJanuary 2009 update: The platform is not active and no recommendations were implemented.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Bioplastic]]s\n* [[FlandersBio]]\n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.europabio.org/articles/article_282_EN.doc From the farmer\u2019s field to your compost heap: how bioplastics will reduce waste]\n* [http://www.belspo.be/belspo/home/actua/2006_03_30_BIPIB_en.pdf Recommendations for industrial biotechnology]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121119015600/http://www.bio-economy.net/bioeconomy/member_states/belgium/files/report_belgium_final01.pdf Country report of Bio-based economy: January 2009 update - page 6 II.A.i]\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-stub}}\n", "text_old": "The '''Belgian Interdisciplinary Platform for Industrial Biotechnology''' or '''BIPIB''' is a [[Belgium|Belgian]] organization which consists of three working groups which come together on [[biomass]] supply, bioprocesses and [[bioproduct]]s, [[bio-energy]]. It was founded by [[Els Van Weert]], [[Flanders|Flemish]] secretary for [[sustainable development]] and [[social economy]]. The BIPIB was given the mission to provide advise for a long-term strategy for developing [[industrial biotechnology]] in Belgium.\n\nJanuary 2009 update: The platform is not active and no recommendations were implemented.\n\n==See also==\n* [[FlandersBio]]\n* [[Bioplastic]]s \n\n==Sources==\n* [http://www.europabio.org/articles/article_282_EN.doc From the farmer\u2019s field to your compost heap: how bioplastics will reduce waste]\n* [http://www.belspo.be/belspo/home/actua/2006_03_30_BIPIB_en.pdf Recommendations for industrial biotechnology]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121119015600/http://www.bio-economy.net/bioeconomy/member_states/belgium/files/report_belgium_final01.pdf Country report of Bio-based economy: January 2009 update - page 6 II.A.i]\n\n[[Category:Science and technology in Belgium]]\n\n\n{{Belgium-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Me, Myself, and I are Here", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also:alpha", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BIPIB"}
{"title_page": "An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer\n| type         = live\n| artist       = [[Tom Lehrer]]\n| cover        = An_Evening_Wasted_With_Tom_Lehrer.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 1959\n| recorded     = March, 1959\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Satire]]\n| length       = 42:23\n| label        = Lehrer Records<br>[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[Songs by Tom Lehrer]]\n| prev_year    = 1953\n| next_title   = [[More of Tom Lehrer]]\n| next_year    = 1959\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Allmusic.com|title=An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer|author=Lehrer, Tom|date=March 1959|location=Cambridge, MA}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer''''' is an [[album]] recorded by [[Tom Lehrer]], the well-known satirist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] lecturer. The recording was made on March 20\u201321, 1959 in [[Sanders Theater]] at Harvard.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Poisoning Pigeons in the Park\"<ref>cf. \"Fr\u00fchlingslied\" (''Geh'mer Tauben vergiften im Park'', \u201cLet's go poisoning pigeons in the park\u201d) on the 10\" album ''Vienna Midnight Cabaret'' by [[Georg Kreisler]] (1957)</ref> \u2013 2:38\n#\"Bright College Days\" \u2013 3:03\n#\"A Christmas Carol\" \u2013 2:54\n#\"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\" \u2013 2:16\n#\"Oedipus Rex\" \u2013 3:41\n#\"In Old Mexico\" \u2013 6:26\n#\"Clementine\" \u2013 4:40\n#\"It Makes a Fellow Proud to Be a Soldier\" \u2013 4:50\n#\"She's My Girl\" \u2013 2:53\n#\"The Masochism Tango\" \u2013 3:30\n#\"We Will All Go Together When We Go\" \u2013 5:32\n\n==Songs' sources==\n\n===\"Poisoning Pigeons in the Park\"===\nThe lyrics refer to killing pigeons with [[strychnine]]-treated corn, a method used by the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] to control pigeon populations in Boston public areas during the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite paper |last=Faulkner |first=Clarence |date=1999-05-01 |title=As It Was in Region 5,1949-1964 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=icwdmprobe |journal=The Probe |volume=200 |pages=7 |via=DigitalCommons@University of Nebraska - Lincoln, \"City-wide pigeon control in Boston, MA using strychnine-treated whole corn\"}}</ref> The pianist hired for the studio-recorded album, ''More of Tom Lehrer'', fell off his bench when he heard the title.<ref>{{cite web|website=Paul-Lehrman.com|url=http://www.paul-lehrman.com/insider/1997/12insiderfulltext.html|title=Insider|date=1997}}</ref>\n\n===\"Bright College Days\"===\nThis song borrows heavily from \"[[The Whiffenpoofs#\"The Whiffenpoof Song\"|The Whiffenpoof Song]]\", the traditional signature song of the [[Yale University|Yale]] [[The Whiffenpoofs|Whiffenpoofs]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n===\"The Elements\"===\n{{main|The Elements (song)}}\n \nThe lyrics of \"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\"<ref>{{cite web|website=privatehand.com|author=Lehrer, Tom|url=http://www.privatehand.com/flash/elements.html |title= The Elements}} (Flash animation)</ref> are a recitation of the names of all the [[chemical element]]s that were known at the time of writing, up to number 102, [[nobelium]]. It can be found on his albums ''[[Songs & More Songs by Tom Lehrer]]'' as well as ''An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer''. The song is sung to the tune of [[Arthur Sullivan|Sir Arthur Sullivan]]'s \"[[Major General's Song]]\" (\"I am the very model of a modern major-general...\") from ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.  Since that time, 16 more have been [[discovery of the chemical elements|discovered]]. At his concert in Copenhagen (1967), Lehrer admitted, \"I like to play this song every once in a while, just to see if I can still do it!\" Indeed, several of Lehrer's fans, such as actor Daniel Radcliffe, have tried and failed to sing it. That is, he sung it in its entirety, but with slight hiccups.<ref>{{YouTube|rSAaiYKF0cs|\"Daniel Radcliffe sings The Elements Song on The Graham Norton Show\"}}, broadcast November 12, 2010</ref> At some concerts he also played a version he claims is based on [[Aristotle]]'s elements: \"There's [[Earth (classical element)|earth]] and [[Air (classical element)|air]] and [[Fire (classical element)|fire]] and [[Water (classical element)|water]].\"<ref>{{YouTube|kSKKPuNoA1g|\"Tom Lehrer performs alternate \"Aristotle\" version\"}}, clip from a live performance in 1967</ref>\n\n===\"Oedipus Rex\"===\nLehrer comments that most popular movies of the time have a catchy title song that helps to draw in audiences. Believing that a recent (1957) [[Oedipus Rex (1957 film)|film adaptation]] of [[Sophocles]]' play ''[[Oedipus Rex]]'' had failed at the box office because it did not have such a song, he wrote this one in [[ragtime]] style.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n \n===\"Clementine\"===\n\"Clementine\" is a parody of the old folk song \"[[Oh My Darling, Clementine]]\" as it might have turned out had it had been written by various composers in widely different styles of music. The first verse was in the style of [[Cole Porter]] (suggestive of \"Night and Day\"); the second verse an [[aria]] for [[baritone]] in the style of [[Mozart]] \"or [[classical music|one of that crowd]]\"; the third verse in the style of the [[Beatnik]] \"Cool School\" (suggestive of [[Thelonious Monk]]'s \"[[52nd Street Theme]]\"); and the rousing finale was, in Lehrer's paraphrase of [[Shakespeare]], \"full of words and music, and signifying nothing,\" in the style of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] (suggestive of \"[[The Sorcerer#Synopsis|My name is John Wellington Wells]]\" or other patter songs). Lehrer's argument for rewriting the song is that folk songs in general are \"so atrocious, because they're written 'by the people',\" and that the original \"Clementine\" has \"no recognizable merit whatsoever.\"\n\n===\"It Makes a Fellow Proud to Be a Soldier\"===\nA parody of the official songs in use by the various branches of the United States military. Lehrer explains that the Army \"didn't have no official song\" when he started basic training; he wrote this one in an attempt to remedy the situation. (The branch adopted \"[[The Army Goes Rolling Along]]\" as its song in 1956, one year after Lehrer enlisted.<ref name=\"AR 220-90\">[http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/r220_90.pdf Army Regulation 220-90,] ''Army Bands'', 14 December 2007, para 2-5f, g</ref>)\n\nOne of the rare parodies of Lehrer's work emerged in [[Jim Bouton]]'s classic book ''[[Ball Four]]'': \"It Makes a Fellow Proud to be an Astro\", conjured up by members of the 1969 [[Houston Astros]].<ref>[http://www.spikesnstars.com/forums/index.php?topic=108076.0;imode]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[That Was the Year That Was]]'' (1965 live album)\n*\"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\"\n*''[[Revisited (Tom Lehrer album)|Revisited]]''\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tom Lehrer}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer, An}}\n[[Category:Tom Lehrer albums]]\n[[Category:1959 live albums]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Satirical works]]\n[[Category:1950s comedy albums]]\n[[Category:Live comedy albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer\n| type         = live\n| artist       = [[Tom Lehrer]]\n| cover        = An_Evening_Wasted_With_Tom_Lehrer.jpg\n| alt          = \n| released     = 1959\n| recorded     = March, 1959\n| venue        = \n| studio       = \n| genre        = [[Satire]]\n| length       = 42:23\n| label        = Lehrer Records<br>[[Reprise Records|Reprise]]/[[Warner Bros. Records]]\n| producer     = \n| prev_title   = [[Songs by Tom Lehrer]]\n| prev_year    = 1953\n| next_title   = [[More of Tom Lehrer]]\n| next_year    = 1959\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[Allmusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|5|5}}<ref>{{cite book|publisher=Allmusic.com|title=An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer|author=Lehrer, Tom|date=March 1959|location=Cambridge, MA}}</ref>\n| rev2      = \n| rev2Score = \n}}\n'''''An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer''''' is an [[album]] recorded by [[Tom Lehrer]], the well-known satirist and [[Harvard University|Harvard]] lecturer. The recording was made on March 20\u201321, 1959 in [[Sanders Theater]] at Harvard.\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"Poisoning Pigeons in the Park\"<ref>cf. \"Fr\u00fchlingslied\" (''Geh'mer Tauben vergiften im Park'', \u201cLet's go poisoning pigeons in the park\u201d) on the 10\" album ''Vienna Midnight Cabaret'' by [[Georg Kreisler]] (1957)</ref> \u2013 2:38\n#\"Bright College Days\" \u2013 3:03\n#\"A Christmas Carol\" \u2013 2:54\n#\"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\" \u2013 2:16\n#\"Oedipus Rex\" \u2013 3:41\n#\"In Old Mexico\" \u2013 6:26\n#\"Clementine\" \u2013 4:40\n#\"It Makes a Fellow Proud to Be a Soldier\" \u2013 4:50\n#\"She's My Girl\" \u2013 2:53\n#\"The Masochism Tango\" \u2013 3:30\n#\"We Will All Go Together When We Go\" \u2013 5:32\n\n==Songs' sources==\n\n===\"Poisoning Pigeons in the Park\"===\nThe lyrics refer to killing pigeons with [[strychnine]]-treated corn, a method used by the [[United States Fish and Wildlife Service]] to control pigeon populations in Boston public areas during the 1950s.<ref>{{Cite paper |last=Faulkner |first=Clarence |date=1999-05-01 |title=As It Was in Region 5,1949-1964 |url=http://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=icwdmprobe |journal=The Probe |volume=200 |pages=7 |via=DigitalCommons@University of Nebraska - Lincoln, \"City-wide pigeon control in Boston, MA using strychnine-treated whole corn\"}}</ref> The pianist hired for the studio-recorded album, ''More of Tom Lehrer'', fell off his bench when he heard the title.<ref>{{cite web|website=Paul-Lehrman.com|url=http://www.paul-lehrman.com/insider/1997/12insiderfulltext.html|title=Insider|date=1997}}</ref>\n\n===\"Bright College Days\"===\nThis song borrows heavily from \"[[The Whiffenpoofs#\"The Whiffenpoof Song\"|The Whiffenpoof Song]]\", the traditional signature song of the [[Yale University|Yale]] [[The Whiffenpoofs|Whiffenpoofs]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n===\"The Elements\"===\n{{main|The Elements (song)}}\n \nThe lyrics of \"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\"<ref>{{cite web|website=privatehand.com|author=Lehrer, Tom|url=http://www.privatehand.com/flash/elements.html |title= The Elements}} (Flash animation)</ref> are a recitation of the names of all the [[chemical element]]s that were known at the time of writing, up to number 102, [[nobelium]]. It can be found on his albums ''[[Songs & More Songs by Tom Lehrer]]'' as well as ''An Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer''. The song is sung to the tune of [[Arthur Sullivan|Sir Arthur Sullivan]]'s \"[[Major General's Song]]\" (\"I am the very model of a modern major-general...\") from ''[[The Pirates of Penzance]]''.  Since that time, 16 more have been [[discovery of the chemical elements|discovered]]. At his concert in Copenhagen (1967), Lehrer admitted, \"I like to play this song every once in a while, just to see if I can still do it!\" Indeed, several of Lehrer's fans, such as actor Daniel Radcliffe, have tried and failed to sing it. That is, he sung it in its entirety, but with slight hiccups.<ref>{{YouTube|rSAaiYKF0cs|\"Daniel Radcliffe sings The Elements Song on The Graham Norton Show\"}}, broadcast November 12, 2010</ref> At some concerts he also played a version he claims is based on [[Aristotle]]'s elements: \"There's [[Earth (classical element)|earth]] and [[Air (classical element)|air]] and [[Fire (classical element)|fire]] and [[Water (classical element)|water]].\"<ref>{{YouTube|kSKKPuNoA1g|\"Tom Lehrer performs alternate Aristotle version\"}}, clip from a live performance in 1967</ref>\n\n===\"Oedipus Rex\"===\nLehrer comments that most popular movies of the time have a catchy title song that helps to draw in audiences. Believing that a recent (1957) [[Oedipus Rex (1957 film)|film adaptation]] of [[Sophocles]]' play ''[[Oedipus Rex]]'' had failed at the box office because it did not have such a song, he wrote this one in [[ragtime]] style.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n \n===\"Clementine\"===\n\"Clementine\" is a parody of the old folk song \"[[Oh My Darling, Clementine]]\" as it might have turned out had it had been written by various composers in widely different styles of music. The first verse was in the style of [[Cole Porter]] (suggestive of \"Night and Day\"); the second verse an [[aria]] for [[baritone]] in the style of [[Mozart]] \"or [[classical music|one of that crowd]]\"; the third verse in the style of the [[Beatnik]] \"Cool School\" (suggestive of [[Thelonious Monk]]'s \"[[52nd Street Theme]]\"); and the rousing finale was, in Lehrer's paraphrase of [[Shakespeare]], \"full of words and music, and signifying nothing,\" in the style of [[Gilbert and Sullivan]] (suggestive of \"[[The Sorcerer#Synopsis|My name is John Wellington Wells]]\" or other patter songs). Lehrer's argument for rewriting the song is that folk songs in general are \"so atrocious, because they're written 'by the people',\" and that the original \"Clementine\" has \"no recognizable merit whatsoever.\"\n\n===\"It Makes a Fellow Proud to Be a Soldier\"===\nA parody of the official songs in use by the various branches of the United States military. Lehrer explains that the Army \"didn't have no official song\" when he started basic training; he wrote this one in an attempt to remedy the situation. (The branch adopted \"[[The Army Goes Rolling Along]]\" as its song in 1956, one year after Lehrer enlisted.<ref name=\"AR 220-90\">[http://www.apd.army.mil/pdffiles/r220_90.pdf Army Regulation 220-90,] ''Army Bands'', 14 December 2007, para 2-5f, g</ref>)\n\nOne of the rare parodies of Lehrer's work emerged in [[Jim Bouton]]'s classic book ''[[Ball Four]]'': \"It Makes a Fellow Proud to be an Astro\", conjured up by members of the 1969 [[Houston Astros]].<ref>[http://www.spikesnstars.com/forums/index.php?topic=108076.0;imode]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[That Was the Year That Was]]'' (1965 live album)\n*\"[[The Elements (song)|The Elements]]\"\n*''[[Revisited (Tom Lehrer album)|Revisited]]''\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tom Lehrer}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Evening Wasted with Tom Lehrer, An}}\n[[Category:Tom Lehrer albums]]\n[[Category:1959 live albums]]\n[[Category:Reprise Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Warner Records live albums]]\n[[Category:Satirical works]]\n[[Category:1950s comedy albums]]\n[[Category:Live comedy albums]]\n", "name_user": "Michael.jacobson", "label": "safe", "comment": "Amended punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An_Evening_Wasted_with_Tom_Lehrer"}
{"title_page": "Isabel Franc", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Isabel Franc\n| image           = Isabel Franc a l\u2019hort de Ca la Dona (cropped).jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth year and age|1955}}\n| birth_place     = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| death_cause     = \n| other_names     = Lola Van Guardia\n| occupation      = Writer\n| employer        = {{ill|Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s|ca}}\n| years_active    = \n| known_for       = \n| notable_works   = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| awards          = {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena}} (2011)\n| alma_mater      = \n}}\n'''Isabel Franc''' (born 1955) is a Spanish writer who signs some of her novels with the pseudonym '''Lola Van Guardia'''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.larioja.com/prensa/20061102/sociedad/reivindicar-porque-nombra-existe_20061102.html |title='Hay que reivindicar lo gay porque lo que no se nombra no existe' |trans-title='You Have to Claim Gayness Because What is Not Named Does Not Exist' |first=Diego |last=Mar\u00edn |work=La Rioja |location=Logro\u00f1o |language=Spanish |date=2 November 2006 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIsabel Franc's works are characterized by humor and being generally focused on the world of [[Lesbian|female homosexuality]]. She has also given lectures and writing courses and she has been invited to talk by American universities. Her style combines satire, irony, and parody in a universe where women are the protagonists.\n<!-- Can't find this quote on elpais.com:\n{{Quote|Write with sarcasm and tenderness in equal parts about beings that could swarm through a Woody Allen movie even if they always have one foot in one of Almod\u00f3var's.|source=''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''}}\n-->\n\nSince 2010 she has been a professor at the {{ill|Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s|ca}} where she teaches courses in writing and humorous literature.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://campusdeescritura.com/inline/ES/profesorado/40/0 |title=Isabel Franc |publisher=Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s |language=Spanish |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref> She has written as a columnist. She is currently (2018) a regular contributor to ''La Independent, Agencia de Noticias con Visi\u00f3n de G\u00e9nero'' (The Independent, News Agency with a Gender Perspective).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laindependent.cat/index.php?option=com_tag&task=tag&tag=isabel-franc |title=Isabel Franc |publisher=La Independent, Agencia de Noticias con Visi\u00f3n de G\u00e9nero |language=Catalan |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Novels===\nFranc made her literary debut with ''Entre todas las mujeres'' (Tusquets, 1992), a {{ill|La sonrisa vertical|es|lt=La Sonrisa Vertical}} Prize finalist.<ref name=Sonrisa>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrO5b1V0j1cC&lpg=PA130&pg=PA130 |title=Crossing Through Chueca: Lesbian Literary Culture in Queer Madrid |first=Jill |last=Robbins |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |isbn=9780816669899 |page=130 |year=2011 |access-date=26 August 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.planetadelibros.com/libro-entre-todas-las-mujeres/89721 |title=Entre todas las mujeres |publisher=[[Grupo Planeta]] |language=Spanish |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is the author of the celebrated Lola Van Guardia Trilogy, published by Egales, which includes the titles ''Con Pedigree'' (1997), ''Plumas de Doble Filo'' (1999), and ''La mansi\u00f3n de las Tr\u00edbadas'' (2002), and has been translated into several languages.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMXBQJwyNRgC&lpg=PA79&pg=PA79 |title=Hispanic and Luso-Brazilian Detective Fiction: Essays on the Genero Negro Tradition |chapter='A World Beyond': The Lola Van Guardia Trilogy |first=Jacky |last=Collins |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=9780786424269 |pages=79\u201390 |date=6 March 2006 |access-date=26 August 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004 she published ''No me llames cari\u00f1o'' (Egales), that received the Shangay Prize for the best novel of the year.<ref name=Quiles>{{Cite web |url=http://www.felgtb.org/temas/politicas-lesbicas/noticias/i/392/222/iii-premios-jennifer-quiles  |title=III Premios Jennifer Quiles |trans-title=3rd Jennifer Quiles Awards |publisher=[[Federaci\u00f3n Estatal de Lesbianas, Gays, Transexuales y Bisexuales]] |language=Spanish |date=1 April 2011 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 ''Las razones de Jo'' (Lumen) was described as \"an unusual, funny, and irreverent version of ''Little Women''.\"\n\nIn 2012 ''Elogio del Happy End'' (Egales) was the winner of the 6th {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena|lt=Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative}}.<ref name=Moix>{{Cite magazine |url=http://www.revistanois.com/2012/09/isabel-franc-gana-el-premio-fundacion-arena/ |title=Isabel Franc gana el Premio Fundaci\u00f3n Arena |trans-title=Isabel Franc Wins the Arena Foundation Award |work=Nois |language=Spanish |date=22 September 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411173840/http://www.revistanois.com/2012/09/isabel-franc-gana-el-premio-fundacion-arena/ |archive-date=11 April 2013 |url-status=dead |access-date=26 August 2018 |magazine= }}</ref>\n\n===Short stories===\n''Cuentos y f\u00e1bulas de Lola Van Guardia'' (Egales, 2008) is a collection of short stories.\n\n===Collective works===\nFranc's [[collective work]]s include ''Otras Voces'' (Egales, 2002), ''Las chicas con las chicas'' (Egales, 2008), ''Noves dames del crim'' (Llibres del Delicte, 2015), ''\u00c1breme con cuidado'' (Dos Bigotes, 2015), ''Incidente en el sal\u00f3n'' (a parody of [[Natalie Clifford Barney|Natalie Barney]]'s famous salon in the Parisian [[Rive Gauche]] in the 1920s), and ''Donde no puedas amar no te demores'' (Egales 2016).\n\n===Graphic novels===\nIn 2010 she published, along with the cartoonist {{ill|Susanna Mart\u00edn|es}}, ''Alicia en un mundo real'' (Norma c\u00f3mic), a graphic novel about breast cancer, not without its irony, which received the 2011 Jennifer Quiles Award.<ref name=Quiles/>\n\nIn 2014, again in collaboration with Susanna Mart\u00edn and Norma c\u00f3mic, Franc published ''Sansamba'', another graphic novel with autobiographical touches, a reflection on cultural and emotional boundaries based on a supposedly impossible friendship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2015/09/25/fotorrelato/1443198512_710406.html#foto_gal_8 |title=P\u00e1ginas plagadas de hero\u00ednas |trans-title=Pages Plagued By Heroines |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] Semanal |page=8 |language=Spanish |date=25 September 2015 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Essays===\nFranc's essays include \"Del pozo a la hiena: humor e iron\u00eda en la llamada literatura l\u00e9sbica\" in the collective volume ''Cultura, homosexualidad y homofobia. Vol II Amazonia: retos de visibilidad lesbiana'' (Laertes 2007) and \"Envers un Elogi del happy end\", in ''Accions i reinvencions. Cultures l\u00e9sbiques a la Catalunya del tombant de segle XXI'' (UOC, 2012).\n\nIn 2013 the collective book ''Desconocidas & Fascinantes'' (Egales) compiled minibiographies to bring visibility to silenced women.\n\nIn 2017, Franc coordinated and edited ''Las Humoristas. Ensayo poco serio sobre mujeres y humor'', published by Icaria. In a humorous tone, the book makes a profound reflection upon the presence and absence of women in the field of humor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eldiario.es/norte/cantabria/cultura/Libreria_La_Voragine-Presentacion-Libro-Humoristas-Ensayo_0_629237325.html |title=Tumbando la falacia de que las mujeres no tienen humor |trans-title=Toppling the Fallacy that Women Do Not Have Humor |first=Rub\u00e9n |last=Alonso |work=[[Eldiario.es]] |language=Spanish |date=3 April 2017 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Translation and editing===\nShe translated ''El jard\u00edn de Shahrzad'' (Egales, 2008) and edited and prefaced the new version of ''[[Ladies Almanack]]'' by [[Djuna Barnes]] (Egales, 2008).<ref name=Quiles/>\n\n===Theater===\nFranc participated in the theatrical production ''Yo soy Gloria Fuertes'' by Gloria Bosch, directed by Ariadna Mart\u00ed de Puig.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.acec-web.org/spa/article.asp?ID=2573 |title=Yo soy Gloria Fuertes |publisher=Asociaci\u00f3n Colegial de Escritores de Catalu\u00f1a |language=Spanish |date=20 February 2018 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref> She is the author of the play ''De Generacions'', a text for three characters that shows how two generations separated by time understand, live, and express feminism.\n\n==Awards==\n* 1992: {{ill|La sonrisa vertical|es|lt=La Sonrisa Vertical}} Prize finalist<ref name=Sonrisa/>\n* 2004: Shangay Award<ref name=Quiles/>\n* 2011: Jennifer Quiles Award<ref name=Quiles/>\n* 2011: {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena}}<ref name=Moix/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[http://isabelfranc.blogspot.com/ Una c\u00f3mica de la pluma]'' \u2013 blog by Isabel Franc\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franc, Isabel}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:Spanish women educators]]\n[[Category:Catalan novelists]]\n[[Category:Catalan short story writers]]\n[[Category:Lesbian writers]]\n[[Category:LGBT writers from Spain]]\n[[Category:LGBT novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Spanish women essayists]]\n[[Category:Spanish women short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language LGBT writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish writer|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Isabel Franc\n| image           = Isabel Franc a l\u2019hort de Ca la Dona (cropped).jpg\n| alt             = \n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth year and age|1955}}\n| birth_place     = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     = \n| death_cause     = \n| other_names     = Lola Van Guardia\n| occupation      = Writer\n| employer        = {{ill|Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s|ca}}\n| years_active    = \n| known_for       = \n| notable_works   = \n| spouse          = \n| children        = \n| awards          = {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena}} (2011)\n| alma_mater      = \n}}\n'''Isabel Franc''' (born 1955) is a Spanish writer who signs some of her novels with the pseudonym '''Lola Van Guardia'''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.larioja.com/prensa/20061102/sociedad/reivindicar-porque-nombra-existe_20061102.html |title='Hay que reivindicar lo gay porque lo que no se nombra no existe' |trans-title='You Have to Claim Gayness Because What is Not Named Does Not Exist' |first=Diego |last=Mar\u00edn |work=La Rioja |location=Logro\u00f1o |language=Spanish |date=2 November 2006 |access-date=25 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIsabel Franc's works are characterized by humor and being generally focused on the world of [[Lesbian|female homosexuality]]. She has also given lectures and writing courses and she has been invited to talk by American universities. Her style combines satire, irony, and parody in a universe where women are the protagonists.\n<!-- Can't find this quote on elpais.com:\n{{Quote|Write with sarcasm and tenderness in equal parts about beings that could swarm through a Woody Allen movie even if they always have one foot in one of Almod\u00f3var's.|source=''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''}}\n-->\n\nSince 2010 she has been a professor at the {{ill|Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s|ca}} where she teaches courses in writing and humorous literature.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://campusdeescritura.com/inline/ES/profesorado/40/0 |title=Isabel Franc |publisher=Ateneu Barcelon\u00e8s |language=Spanish |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref> She has written as a columnist. She is currently (2018) a regular contributor to ''La Independent, Agencia de Noticias con Visi\u00f3n de G\u00e9nero'' (The Independent, News Agency with a Gender Perspective).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.laindependent.cat/index.php?option=com_tag&task=tag&tag=isabel-franc |title=Isabel Franc |publisher=La Independent, Agencia de Noticias con Visi\u00f3n de G\u00e9nero |language=Catalan |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n===Novels===\nFranc made her literary debut with ''Entre todas las mujeres'' (Tusquets, 1992), a {{ill|La sonrisa vertical|es|lt=La Sonrisa Vertical}} Prize finalist.<ref name=Sonrisa>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zrO5b1V0j1cC&lpg=PA130&pg=PA130 |title=Crossing Through Chueca: Lesbian Literary Culture in Queer Madrid |first=Jill |last=Robbins |publisher=[[University of Minnesota Press]] |isbn=9780816669899 |page=130 |year=2011 |access-date=26 August 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.planetadelibros.com/libro-entre-todas-las-mujeres/89721 |title=Entre todas las mujeres |publisher=[[Grupo Planeta]] |language=Spanish |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is the author of the celebrated Lola Van Guardia Trilogy, published by Egales, which includes the titles ''Con Pedigree'' (1997), ''Plumas de Doble Filo'' (1999), and ''La mansi\u00f3n de las Tr\u00edbadas'' (2002), and has been translated into several languages.<ref>{{Cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lMXBQJwyNRgC&lpg=PA79&pg=PA79 |title=Hispanic and Luso-Brazilian Detective Fiction: Essays on the Genero Negro Tradition |chapter='A World Beyond': The Lola Van Guardia Trilogy |first=Jacky |last=Collins |publisher=[[McFarland & Company]] |isbn=9780786424269 |pages=79\u201390 |date=6 March 2006 |access-date=26 August 2018 |via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2004 she published ''No me llames cari\u00f1o'' (Egales), that received the Shangay Prize for the best novel of the year.<ref name=Quiles>{{Cite web |url=http://www.felgtb.org/temas/politicas-lesbicas/noticias/i/392/222/iii-premios-jennifer-quiles  |title=III Premios Jennifer Quiles |trans-title=3rd Jennifer Quiles Awards |publisher=[[Federaci\u00f3n Estatal de Lesbianas, Gays, Transexuales y Bisexuales]] |language=Spanish |date=1 April 2011 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 ''Las razones de Jo'' (Lumen) was described as \"an unusual, funny, and irreverent version of ''Little Women''.\"\n\nIn 2012 ''Elogio del Happy End'' (Egales) was the winner of the 6th {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena|lt=Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative}}.<ref name=Moix>{{Cite magazine |url=http://www.revistanois.com/2012/09/isabel-franc-gana-el-premio-fundacion-arena/ |title=Isabel Franc gana el Premio Fundaci\u00f3n Arena |trans-title=Isabel Franc Wins the Arena Foundation Award |work=Nois |language=Spanish |date=22 September 2012 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130411173840/http://www.revistanois.com/2012/09/isabel-franc-gana-el-premio-fundacion-arena/ |archive-date=11 April 2013 |url-status=dead |access-date=26 August 2018 |magazine= }}</ref>\n\n===Short stories===\n''Cuentos y f\u00e1bulas de Lola Van Guardia'' (Egales, 2008) is a collection of short stories.\n\n===Collective works===\nFranc's [[collective work]]s include ''Otras Voces'' (Egales, 2002), ''Las chicas con las chicas'' (Egales, 2008), ''Noves dames del crim'' (Llibres del Delicte, 2015), ''\u00c1breme con cuidado'' (Dos Bigotes, 2015), ''Incidente en el sal\u00f3n'' (a parody of [[Natalie Clifford Barney|Natalie Barney]]'s famous salon in the Parisian [[Rive Gauche]] in the 1920s), and ''Donde no puedas amar no te demores'' (Egales 2016).\n\n===Graphic novels===\nIn 2010 she published, along with the cartoonist {{ill|Susanna Mart\u00edn|es}}, ''Alicia en un mundo real'' (Norma c\u00f3mic), a graphic novel about breast cancer, not without its irony, which received the 2011 Jennifer Quiles Award.<ref name=Quiles/>\n\nIn 2014, again in collaboration with Susanna Mart\u00edn and Norma c\u00f3mic, Franc published ''Sansamba'', another graphic novel with autobiographical touches, a reflection on cultural and emotional boundaries based on a supposedly impossible friendship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://elpais.com/elpais/2015/09/25/fotorrelato/1443198512_710406.html#foto_gal_8 |title=P\u00e1ginas plagadas de hero\u00ednas |trans-title=Pages Plagued By Heroines |work=[[El Pa\u00eds]] Semanal |page=8 |language=Spanish |date=25 September 2015 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Essays===\nFranc's essays include \"Del pozo a la hiena: humor e iron\u00eda en la llamada literatura l\u00e9sbica\" in the collective volume ''Cultura, homosexualidad y homofobia. Vol II Amazonia: retos de visibilidad lesbiana'' (Laertes 2007) and \"Envers un Elogi del happy end\", in ''Accions i reinvencions. Cultures l\u00e9sbiques a la Catalunya del tombant de segle XXI'' (UOC, 2012).\n\nIn 2013 the collective book ''Desconocidas & Fascinantes'' (Egales) compiled minibiographies to bring visibility to silenced women.\n\nIn 2017, Franc coordinated and edited ''Las Humoristas. Ensayo poco serio sobre mujeres y humor'', published by Icaria. In a humorous tone, the book makes a profound reflection upon the presence and absence of women in the field of humor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.eldiario.es/norte/cantabria/cultura/Libreria_La_Voragine-Presentacion-Libro-Humoristas-Ensayo_0_629237325.html |title=Tumbando la falacia de que las mujeres no tienen humor |trans-title=Toppling the Fallacy that Women Do Not Have Humor |first=Rub\u00e9n |last=Alonso |work=[[Eldiario.es]] |language=Spanish |date=3 April 2017 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Translation and editing===\nShe translated ''El jard\u00edn de Shahrzad'' (Egales, 2008) and edited and prefaced the new version of ''[[Ladies Almanack]]'' by [[Djuna Barnes]] (Egales, 2008).<ref name=Quiles/>\n\n===Theater===\nFranc participated in the theatrical production ''Yo soy Gloria Fuertes'' by Gloria Bosch, directed by Ariadna Mart\u00ed de Puig.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.acec-web.org/spa/article.asp?ID=2573 |title=Yo soy Gloria Fuertes |publisher=Asociaci\u00f3n Colegial de Escritores de Catalu\u00f1a |language=Spanish |date=20 February 2018 |access-date=26 August 2018}}</ref> She is the author of the play ''De Generacions'', a text for three characters that shows how two generations separated by time understand, live, and express feminism.\n\n==Awards==\n* 1992: {{ill|La sonrisa vertical|es|lt=La Sonrisa Vertical}} Prize finalist<ref name=Sonrisa/>\n* 2004: Shangay Award<ref name=Quiles/>\n* 2011: Jennifer Quiles Award<ref name=Quiles/>\n* 2011: {{ill|Arena Foundation Terenci Moix Award for Gay and Lesbian Narrative|ca|Premi Terenci Moix de Narrativa Gai i L\u00e8sbica Fundaci\u00f3n Arena}}<ref name=Moix/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* ''[http://isabelfranc.blogspot.com/ Una c\u00f3mica de la pluma]'' \u2013 blog by Isabel Franc\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Franc, Isabel}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Spanish women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish educators]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish women writers]]\n