thletic Association]] club.\n\nValentia is a popular fishing location, and Valentia waters hold the Irish records for [[conger eel]], [[red sea bream]], [[Ray's bream]] and [[lesser spotted dogfish]].{{citation needed|date=January 2012}}\n\n==Notable people==\n* [[Helen Blackburn]] who was a leading women's rights campaigner in England was born here in 1842.<ref>{{Cite ODNB|id=31905|title=Blackburn, Helen (1842\u20131903), campaigner for women's rights|first=Linda|last=Walker|year=2004}}</ref>\n* Valentia was considered home to [[Mug Ruith]], a powerful blind [[druid]] in [[Irish mythology]].\n* The O'Sullivans, headed by the [[O'Sullivan Beare]], owned much of Valentia until the 17th century.<ref>{{cite ODNB|id=20913|title=\nO'Sullivan Beare, Philip (b. c.1590, d. in or after 1634)|first=Toby|last=Barnard|year=2004}}</ref>\n* The noted naturalist [[Maude Jane Delap]] lived and worked in Knightstown, carrying out important research into the marine life surrounding Valentia and identifying many new species.<ref name=\"Mulvihill1\">{{cite book|last1=Mulvihill|first1=Mary|title=Ingenious Ireland: A County-by-County Exploration of the Mysteries and Marvels of the Ingenious Irish|date=2003|publisher=Simon and Schuster|location=Dublin|isbn=0684020947|pages=397\u2013398|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=exics12jmtwC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=Maude%20Delap&f=false|accessdate=10 November 2014}}</ref>\n* Valentia is the home of former [[Gaelic football]]er, [[Mick O'Connell]] and the birthplace of [[John J. O'Kelly|John J \"Sc\u00e9ilig\" O'Kelly]], leader of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] from 1926.\n* Gaelic footballer [[Ger O'Driscoll (Gaelic footballer)|Ger O'Driscoll]] was born on Valentia Island.\n* The American solo rock climber [[Michael Reardon (climber)|Michael Reardon]] died on 13 July 2007 at the Fogher Cliffs of Valentia Island when he was swept out to sea following a successful climb.\n* [[Gerald Spring Rice, 6th Baron Monteagle of Brandon]] was brought up on the island, as were many other members of the Spring Rice family.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://guardsmagazine.com/obits_lordmonteagle.html|title=Obituary: Captain The Lord Monteagle of Brandon|website=The Guards Magazine|access-date=16 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903062226/http://guardsmagazine.com/obits_lordmonteagle.html|archive-date=2014-09-03|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Ireland|Islands}}\n* [[List of RNLI stations]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.valentiaisland.ie Valentia Island Portal]\n*[http://vhc.ftldesign.com/ Valentia Heritage Centre]\n*[http://www.valentiaislefestival.com Valentia Island Annual Music Festival]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060727200305/http://www.theroseoftralee.ie/locations/ringofkerry/valentiaisland.htm Travel Information]\n*[http://www.gsi.ie/workgsi/heritage/igh/sites/valentia/track.htm The Tetrapod Trackways]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060912114341/http://beck.library.emory.edu/iln/browse.php?id=iln47.1327.008 The Laying of the Atlantic Telegraph Cable]\n*[http://www.atlantic-cable.com/Article/CableTrail/index.htm Telegraph Cable History Trail]\n*[http://www.atlantic-cable.com/Article/CableTrail/ValentiaHC/index.htm Cable History at the Valentia Heritage Centre]\n*[http://www.alanryanhall.com Alan Hall - Sculptor of the First Transatlantic Cable and First message sent to USA 1856 Memorial ]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=fyCqJ8-BBMAC&pg=PA88&dq=foilhommerum#PPA90,M1 Submarine Telegraphs, Their History, Construction, and Working by Charles Bright]\n*[http://www.profsurv.com/archive.php?issue=89&article=1247 Linking European and American Longitude]\n*[http://www.ieee.org/web/aboutus/history_center/county_kerry.html IEEE History Center: County Kerry Transatlantic Cable Stations, 1866]\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=QoiA4GjAHwwC&pg=RA27-PA54&lpg=RA27-PA54&dq=foilhommerum&source=web&ots=QMAfd_bMVT&sig=UeL-bt3ugcjstwQs9LomoeEN3qU#PRA25-PA53,M1 The Transatlantic Longitude as Determined by the Coast Survey Expedition of 1866]\n*[http://www.valentiaislandseaangling.com Valentia Island Sea Angling]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130621005034/http://www.thetelegraphfield.com/ The Telegraph Field - Valentia Island]\n*[http://www.irelandbyways.com/top-irish-peninsulas/irelands-south/the-southwestern-islands/valentia-island-co-kerry/ Irelandbyways site Valentia Information]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051109024047/http://indigo.ie/~cguiney/valentia.html Valentia Island]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Browne, E.T., The fauna and flora of Valencia Harbour on the west coast of Ireland. ''Proc. R.Ir. Acad.,'' ser.3,5, 667-854\n{{Commonscat-inline}}\n{{Castles in Connacht}}\n{{County Kerry}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Fossil trackways]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox islands\n| name             = Valentia Island\n| image_name       = 046Valencia_Knightstown.JPG\n| image_caption    = Knightstown Town clock\n| map              = island of Ireland\n| map_caption      = Valentia Island\n| native_name      = Dairbhre\n| native_name_link = Irish language\n| nickname         = \n| location         = [[Atlantic Ocean]]\n| coordinates      = {{coord|51.9|-10.35|region:IE_scale:20000_source:Google|display=inline,title}}\n| archipelago      = \n| area_km2         = 25.7<ref name=\"cyclopaedia1867\">{{Cite book|last=Knight|first=Charles|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=igVCAAAAYAAJ&dq=%22valentia%20island%22%20acres&pg=PA387#v=onepage&q=%22valentia%20island%22%20acres&f=false|title=The English Cyclopaedia: Geography|date=1867|publisher=[[Bradbury and Evans|Bradbury, Evans, & Co.]]|location=[[London]]|pages=387|language=en|quote=Valentia Island, which has an area of {{convert|6371|acres|km2}} and is extemely fertile and tolerably well cultivated,[...]|author-link=Charles Knight (publisher)|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n| area_footnotes   =\n| length_km        = 11\n| length_footnotes = \n| width_km         = 3\n| width_footnotes  =\n| coastline_km     = \n| highest_mount    = \n| elevation_m      = \n| country          = [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title     = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n| country_admin_divisions           = [[Munster]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_1   = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n| country_admin_divisions_1         = [[County Kerry|Kerry]]\n| country_admin_divisions_title_2   = \n| country_admin_divisions_2         = \n| country_capital_city              = \n| country_largest_city              = [[Knightstown, County Kerry|Knightstown]]\n| country_largest_city_population   = 156\n| country_leader_title              = \n| country_leader_name               = \n| population       = 665\n| population_as_of = 2011\n| density_km2      = \n| ethnic_groups    = \n| additional_info  =\n}}\n\n'''Valentia Island''' ({{lang-ga|Dairbhre}}, meaning \"The Oak Wood\") is one of [[Ireland]]'s most westerly points. It lies off the [[Iveragh Peninsula]] in the southwest of [[County Kerry]]. It is linked to the mainland by the Maurice O'Neill Memorial Bridge at [[Portmagee]].  A [[Roll-on/roll-off|car ferry]] also departs from [[Reenard Point]] to [[Knightstown, County Kerry|Knightstown]], the [[island]]'s main settlement, from April to October. A second, smaller village named [[Chapeltown, County Kerry|Chapeltown]] is located at roughly the midpoint of the island, {{convert|3|km|mi|abbr=off}} from the bridge. The permanent population of the island is 665 ({{As of|2011|alt=as of the 2011 [[Central Statistics Office of Ireland|CSO Census]]}}).<ref name=census2011>{{cite report| title=Electoral Division Valencia (CSO Area Code ED 19025)| at=Valencia |work=Census of Ireland 2011| volume=1 \u2013 Population Classified by Area| publisher=[[Central Statistics Office of Ireland]]| url=http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2011/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ED&Geog_Code=19025&CTY=19|access-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203015816/http://census.cso.ie/sapmap2011/Results.aspx?Geog_Type=ED&Geog_Code=19025&CTY=19|archive-date=3 December 2013}}</ref> It is approximately {{convert|11|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} long by almost {{convert|3|km|mi|0|abbr=off}} wide.\n\n==Name==\nThe English name Valentia Island (also spelled Valencia Island) doesn't come exactly from the Spanish city of [[Valencia]], but from a settlement on the island called ''An Bhaile Inse'' or ''Beal Inse'' (\"mouth of the island\" or \"island in the mouth of the sound\"), which in turn could have been reinterpreted as similar to the Spanish town by Englishmen and Spaniards sailors and settlers alike (there is a grave marker to Spanish sailors lost at sea in the Catholic cemetery at Kylemore).\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ireland Valentia Island telegraph.JPG|thumb|Telegraph Field, Valentia Island: Foilhommerum is the site of the first permanent communications link between [[Europe]] and [[Americas|the Americas]]. In October 2002, a memorial to mark the laying of the transatlantic cable to [[Heart's Content, Newfoundland and Labrador|Heart's Content]], [[Newfoundland (island)|Newfoundland]] was unveiled atop Foilhommerum Cliff. Made of Valentia slate and designed by local sculptor [http://www.alanryanhall.com Alan Ryan Hall],<ref name=\"hall2011\">{{Cite web|url=http://alanryanhall.com/artwork.asp?a=39&c=1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707104101/http://alanryanhall.com/artwork.asp?a=39&c=1|title=First Transatlantic Cable and First message sent to USA 1856 Memorial by Alan Hall|archive-date=2011-07-07|access-date=2020-03-07|quote=Valentia Slate Memorial, showing cross cuts of cable spanning the Atlantic from 1853 to 1966, Year: 2006, Price: 4,500.00 ({{Inflation|UK|4,500.00|2006|fmt=eq|cursign=\u00a3}})}}</ref> the memorial marks the importance of the site to telegraph communications with North America from 1857 forward and to accurately linking longitude measurements in North America to the Royal Observatory in Greenwich in 1866.]]\n\nValentia was the eastern terminus of the first commercially viable [[transatlantic telegraph cable]].<ref>[http://www.sil.si.edu/digitalcollections/hst/atlantic-cable/SIL4-004-093a.jpg The Atlantic Cable], [[Smithsonian Institution]], USA.</ref> The first attempt in 1857<ref>John R. Isaac, [http://atlantic-cable.com/Books/1857Isaac/ 1857 \u2014 Laying the Atlantic Telegraph Cable from Ship to Shore], History of the Atlantic Cable & Undersea Communications.</ref> to land a cable from Ballycarbery Strand on the mainland just east of Valentia Island ended in disappointment. After subsequent failures of cables landed at Knightstown in 1858 and Foilhommerum Bay in 1865,<ref name=\"telegraphfield\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.thetelegraphfield.com/|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130621005034/http://www.thetelegraphfield.com/|archive-date=2013-06-21|title=The Telegraph Field with transatlantic telegraph cable station - Valentia Island, Ireland - Anglo American Cable House|date=2013-06-21|access-date=2020-03-07|last=Buchanan|first=Keith|quote=Also known as \"'''The Longitude Field\"'''. Prior to the transatlantic telegraph, American [[longitude]] measurements had a {{convert|2800|foot|m}} [[Uncertainty#Measurements|uncertainty]] with respect to European longitudes. A temporary longitude observatory was built adjacent to the Foilhommerum Cable Station to facilitate [[History_of_longitude#Further_refinements_for_longitude_on_land|synchronized longitude observations]] with [[Heart's Content Cable Station|Heart's Content]], Newfoundland.}}</ref> the vast endeavor finally resulted in commercially viable transatlantic telegraph communications from Foilhommerum Bay to [[Heart's Content Cable Station|Heart's Content]], Newfoundland in 1866. Transatlantic telegraph cables operated from Valentia Island for one hundred years, ending with [[Western Union]] International terminating its cable operations in 1966.\n\nPrior to the transatlantic telegraph, American longitude measurements had a {{convert|2800|ft|m|-1|adj=on}} uncertainty with respect to European longitudes. Because of the importance of accurate longitudes to safe navigation, the [[U.S. National Geodetic Survey|U.S. Coast Survey]] mounted a longitude expedition in 1866 to link longitudes in the United States accurately to the [[Royal Observatory, Greenwich|Royal Observatory in Greenwich]].  [[Benjamin Apthorp Gould|Benjamin Gould]] and his partner A. T. Mosman reached Valentia on 2 October 1866. They built a temporary longitude observatory beside the Foilhommerum Cable Station to support synchronized longitude observations with [[Heart's Content, Newfoundland and Labrador|Heart's Content]], Newfoundland.  After many rainy and cloudy days, the first transatlantic longitude signals were exchanged between Foilhommerum and Heart's Content on October 24, 1866.\n\nSaturday, May 21st 1927, Charles A. Lindbergh, on his solo flight from New York to Paris make his first landfall in Europe over Dingle Bay and Valentia island. On the 1927 Mercator chart used by the famous pilot, it was labeled Valencia.<ref name=\"hampton2017\">{{Cite book|last=Hampton|first=Dan|page=189|title=The flight : Charles Lindbergh's daring and immortal 1927 Transatlantic crossing|date=2017|isbn=978-0-06-246439-2|edition=First|location=New York, NY|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|oclc=957504448}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993 an undergraduate geology student discovered fossilised [[tetrapod]] [[fossil trackway|trackway]]s, footprints preserved in [[Devonian]] rocks, on the north coast of the island at Dohilla ({{coord|51.930868|-10.343849|format=dms|type:landmark_region:IE|display=inline}}). About 385 million years ago, a primitive [[vertebrate]] passed near a river margin in the sub-equatorial river basin that is now southwestern Ireland and left prints in the damp sand. The prints were preserved by silt and sand overlying them, and were converted to rock over geological time. The [[Early_tetrapod_trackways#Valentia_Island,_Ireland|Valentia Island trackways]] are among the oldest signs of vertebrate life on land.<ref name=\"stossel2016\">{{Cite journal|last=St\u00f6ssel|first=Iwan|last2=Williams|first2=Edward A.|last3=Higgs|first3=Kenneth T.|date=15 November 2016|title=Ichnology and depositional environment of the Middle Devonian Valentia Island tetrapod trackways, south-west Ireland|journal=Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology|language=en|volume=462|pages=16\u201340|doi=10.1016/j.palaeo.2016.08.033|issn=0031-0182}}</ref><ref name=\"niedzwiedzki\">{{Cite journal|last=Nied\u017awiedzki|first=Grzegorz|last2=Szrek|first2=Piotr|last3=Narkiewicz|first3=Katarzyna|last4=Narkiewicz|first4=Marek|last5=Ahlberg|first5=Per E.|date=January 2010|title=Tetrapod trackways from the early Middle Devonian period of Poland|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=463|issue=7277|pages=43\u201348|doi=10.1038/nature08623|pmid=20054388|issn=1476-4687|quote=Supposed [[Trace fossil|trackways]] of very early tetrapods have been recorded from a number of localities in Europe and Australia. [...] Two large trackways from Valentia Island, Ireland, have been [[Radiometric dating|dated radiometrically]] to 385 million years ago.[...]Figure 5 {{!}} Phylogenetic implications of tracks. [...]The bars are approximate measures of the uncertainty of dating. These are not statistical error bars but an attempt to reflect ongoing debate.}}</ref>\n\n{{Historical populations\n| align = none\n| cols = 3\n|footnote= Source: {{cite web |url= http://www.cso.ie/px/pxeirestat/Statire/SelectVarVal/Define.asp?Maintable=CNA17&Planguage=0 |title= CNA17: Population by Off Shore Island, Sex and Year  |author= Central Statistics Office |date=  |website= CSO.ie |publisher= |accessdate=October 12, 2016}}\n\n|1841|2290\n|1851|2482\n|1861|2240\n|1871|2139\n|1881|2240\n|1891|2050\n|1901|1864\n|1911|1625\n|1926|1483\n|1936|1198\n|1946|1102\n|1951|1015\n|1956|971\n|1961|926\n|1966|847\n|1971|770\n|1979|712\n|1981|718\n|1986|666\n|1991|680\n|1996|676\n|2002|690\n|2006|713\n\n}}\n\n==Places of interest==\n[[File:Valentia Island.jpg|Valentia Harbour from the north shore of Valentia Island (Photo taken at the top of the Catholic cemetery at Kylemore)|thumb|275px|right]]\nThe combined features and history of the island make it an attractive [[Tourist destinations in Ireland|tourist destination]], easily accessible from the popular [[Ring of Kerry]] route.\n*[[Geokaun Mountain and Fogher Cliffs]] : the highest mountain on Valentia Island and the sea cliffs of {{convert|600|ft}} on its northern face.\n*On the northeast of the island stands '''Glanleam House''' amid [[sub-tropical]] gardens. Protected by [[windbreak]]s from Atlantic gales and never touched by frost, these gardens provide the mildest [[microclimate]] in Ireland. Starting in the 1830s, Sir Peter George Fitzgerald, the 19th [[Knight of Kerry]] (1808\u20131880),<ref name=\"proni1998\">{{Cite web|date=29 April 1998|url=http://www.proni.gov.uk/records/private/fitzger.htm|url-status=dead|title=The FitzGerald (Knights of Kerry) Papers (MIC/639 and T/3075)|publisher=[[Public Record Office of Northern Ireland]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927205140/http://www.proni.gov.uk/records/private/fitzger.htm|archive-date=2007-09-27|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"t3075proni\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/fitzgerald-t3075.pdf#page=11|date=November 2007|page=10|title=Introduction to the FitzGerald (Knights of Kerry) Papers (T3075) |publisher=[[Public Record Office of Northern Ireland]]|language=en|access-date=2020-03-07|quote=He showed a keen interest in everything which had a practical bearing on the progress or prosperity of Ireland and, predictably, he was most co-operative in the establishment of the trans-Atlantic cable station at Valentia.|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902010754/https://www.nidirect.gov.uk/sites/default/files/publications/fitzgerald-t3075.pdf|archive-date=2 September 2016}}</ref> planted these gardens and stocked them with a unique collection of rare and tender plants from the southern hemisphere, normally grown under glass in [[Ireland]]. The gardens are laid out in a naturalistic style as a series of walks. There are plants from South America, Australia, New Zealand (the tallest [[tree fern]]s in Europe), Chile and Japan. The gardens are memorialized in a selected golden-variegated ''[[Luma (plant)|Luma apiculata]]'' \"Glanleam Gold\" that originated as a sport in the garden. The gardens are open to the public.\n*The slate quarry which reopened in 1998 provided slates for the British [[Palace of Westminster|Houses of Parliament]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cromane.net/valentia.htm|title=Valentia Island|last=Condon|first=Des|date=2006|website=Cromane Community Council|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080521083448/http://cromane.net/valentia.htm|archive-date=2008-05-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*The island also hosts a heritage centre<ref name=\"heritagecentre\">{{Cite web|url=http://vhc.cablehistory.org/|title=Valentia Heritage Centre|location=Knightstown, Valentia Island, Co. Kerry, Ireland|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928185226/http://vhc.cablehistory.org/|archive-date=28 September 2007|access-date=2020-03-07|url-status=live}}</ref> which tells the story of the geology, human, natural and industrial history of the island, with exhibits on the Cable Station, the Marine Radio Station and the [[RNLI]]'s [[Valentia Lifeboat Station]].\n*The Telegraph Field (or Longitude Field) is the site of the first permanent communications link between Europe and North America [[Transatlantic telegraph cable]]s operated from Valentia Island from 1866.<ref name=\"telegraphfield\" />\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:IMG 4298 Dolmen Rock 1.jpg|Dolmen Rock, western slope of Mt. Geokaun\nFile:IMG 4371 Balleyhearney House 1.jpg|Balleyhearney House, Balleyhearney East. 'Famine Era' hospital adjacent to the Knights' Wood.\nFile:IMG 9407 Rare Snow Day Main Road Valentia Island.jpg|Rare snowy day, Main Road, Valentia Island looking toward Knightstown, Valentia Harbour and Cahirciveen\nFile:IMG 9227 View from Mt Geokuan Summit 2.jpg|Portion of the view from the summit of Mt. Geokaun (\"yo-kawn\"). Valentia Harbour and Cahirciveen are in the background \nFile:9228 View from Mt Geokuan Summit 3.jpg|Portion of the view from the summit of Mt. Geokaun (\"yo-kawn\"). Valentia Harbour and Letter are in the background\nFile:IMG 5110 CullooRock 1.jpg|View from Culloo Rock. Dingle Peninsula, Dingle Bay and the north shore of Valentia Island (including Fogher Cliffs) are in the background.\nFile:Bray Head, Valentia Island.jpg|Bray Head view looking west with Skellig Islands in distance\nFile:Portmagee Channel from Bray.jpg|View of Portmagee Channel looking south-east from Bray Head\nFile:Valentia lighthouse.jpg|Valentia lighthouse and surrounding fortifications\nFile:Knightstown aerial.jpg|Knightstown\nFile:Glanleam House.jpg|Glanleam House\nFile:Slate Quarry.jpg|Valentia Slate Quarry\n</gallery>\n\n==Climate==\nThe Valentia Island Weather Station is located 51\u00b0 56' 23\"N, 10\u00b0 14'40\"W and is {{convert|25|m|ft|abbr=off}} [[above mean sea level]]. It is one of the [[List of coastal weather stations in the British Isles|22 coastal weather stations]] whose reports are broadcast as part of the [[Shipping Forecast|BBC Shipping Forecast]]. Valentia Observatory is part of Met \u00c9ireann, the Irish Meteorological Service. The observatory was set up in August 1868. Valentia island is, on average, the wettest weather station in Ireland. The monthly averages for Sunshine and Rainfall are based on 2010 statistics which are around average apart from July, which received only 40% of its normal sunshine hours and 219% of its normal rainfall. Valentia island also has a station for [[Navtex]] transmissions. Valentia Island sits on the eastern edge of the Atlantic Ocean. Despite it being on the same latitude as [[St. Anthony, Newfoundland and Labrador|St. Anthony]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]] on the opposite side of the Atlantic Ocean, it enjoys much milder winters thanks to the moderating effect of prevailing west or south west winds, and the effects of the warming Gulf Stream current. Snow and frost are rare, and because of this the island can support many sub-tropical varieties of plants.\n{{Weather box\n|location = Valentia Island, [[County Kerry]] (1981\u20132010, extremes 1892\u2013present)\n|metric first = Yes\n|single line = Yes\n|Jan record high C = 14.8\n|Feb record high C = 16.8\n|Mar record high C = 20.7\n|Apr record high C = 24.0\n|May record high C = 27.2\n|Jun record high C = 28.1\n|Jul record high C = 29.7\n|Aug record high C = 29.8\n|Sep record high C = 28.4\n|Oct record high C = 23.9\n|Nov record high C = 19.8\n|Dec record high C = 15.7\n|year record high C = 29.8\n|Jan high C = 9.8\n|Feb high C = 9.8\n|Mar high C = 11.0\n|Apr high C = 12.5\n|May high C = 14.9\n|Jun high C = 16.7\n|Jul high C = 18.1\n|Aug high C = 18.2\n|Sep high C = 17.0\n|Oct high C = 14.3\n|Nov high C = 11.8\n|Dec high C = 10.3\n|year high C = 13.7\n|Jan mean C = 7.3\n|Feb mean C = 7.2\n|Mar mean C = 8.2\n|Apr mean C = 9.4\n|May mean C = 11.6\n|Jun mean C = 13.7\n|Jul mean C = 15.4\n|Aug mean C = 15.4\n|Sep mean C = 14.1\n|Oct mean C = 11.7\n|Nov mean C = 9.3\n|Dec mean C = 7.8\n|year mean C = 10.9\n|Jan low C = 4.7\n|Feb low C = 4.6\n|Mar low C = 5.4\n|Apr low C = 6.3\n|May low C = 8.4\n|Jun low C = 10.8\n|Jul low C = 12.7\n|Aug low C = 12.6\n|Sep low C = 11.2\n|Oct low C = 9.0\n|Nov low C = 6.8\n|Dec low C = 5.3\n|year low C = 8.2\n|Jan record low C = -7.2\n|Feb record low C = -7.3\n|Mar record low C = -5.1\n|Apr record low C = -2.3\n|May record low C = 0.2\n|Jun record low C = 1.7\n|Jul record low C = 4.4\n|Aug record low C = 3.3\n|Sep record low C = 1.7\n|Oct record l